{
  "title": {
    "text": "The operating system must, for password-based\n                        authentication, verify when users create or update passwords the\n                        passwords are not found on the list of commonly-used, expected, or\n                        compromised passwords in IA-5 (1) (a).",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "description": {
    "text": "Password-based authentication applies\n                        to passwords regardless of whether they are used in single-factor or\n                        multifactor authentication. Long passwords or passphrases are preferable\n                        over shorter passwords. Enforced composition rules provide marginal\n                        security benefits while decreasing usability. However, organizations may\n                        choose to establish certain rules for password generation (e.g., minimum\n                        character length for long passwords) under certain circumstances and can\n                        enforce this requirement in IA-5(1)(h). Account recovery can occur, for\n                        example, in situations when a password is forgotten. Cryptographically\n                        protected passwords include salted one-way cryptographic hashes\n                        of passwords. The list of commonly used, compromised, or expected\n                        passwords includes passwords obtained from previous breach corpuses,\n                        dictionary words, and repetitive or sequential characters. The list\n                        includes context-specific words, such as the name of the service,\n                        username, and derivatives thereof.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "rationale": {
    "text": "The container image is built with no local user accounts other\n                        than a locked root. All interactive or programmatic access to the workload\n                        is handled by the container-orchestration platform, which enforces its\n                        own credential hygiene and MFA controls. The OS inside the container\n                        never receives, stores, or validates passwords and no password database\n                        exists against which to apply bad-password screening, forced post-recovery\n                        changes, passphrase-length rules, or password-generation aids.\n\n                        For more information on inherited controls for containers see the DISA\n                        Container Hardening Process Guide.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "platform": {
    "idref": "cpe:/o:notapplicable"
  },
  "ident": {
    "text": "CCI-004061",
    "system": "http://cyber.mil/cci"
  },
  "id": "xccdf_mil.disa.stig_rule_SV-263653r982229_rule",
  "selected": "true",
  "role": "full",
  "severity": "medium"
}

