{
  "title": {
    "text": "The operating system must synchronize system clocks\n                        within and between systems or system components.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "description": {
    "text": "Time synchronization of system clocks is\n                        essential for the correct execution of many system services, including\n                        identification and authentication processes that involve certificates\n                        and time-of-day restrictions as part of access control. Denial of\n                        service or failure to deny expired credentials may result without\n                        properly synchronized clocks within and between systems and system\n                        components. Time is commonly expressed in Coordinated Universal Time\n                        (UTC), a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time\n                        with an offset from UTC. The granularity of time measurements refers\n                        to the degree of synchronization between system clocks and reference\n                        clocks, such as clocks synchronizing within hundreds of milliseconds\n                        or tens of milliseconds. Organizations may define different time\n                        granularities for system components. Time service can be critical to\n                        other security capabilities—such as access control and identification\n                        and authentication—depending on the nature of the mechanisms used to\n                        support the capabilities.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "rationale": {
    "text": "Linux containers inherit the system time from the underlying\n                        host - a separate time service is not operated within the container. The\n                        host owner is responsible for configuring the host's time service to\n                        generate the timestamp used by its auditing system, perform periodic\n                        synchronization, and ensure that only authorized time servers are used\n                        as the authoritative source. Time synchronization of the host clock is\n                        automatically reflected in the time used by the container.\n\n                        For more information on inherited controls for containers see the DISA\n                        Container Hardening Process Guide.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "platform": {
    "idref": "cpe:/o:notapplicable"
  },
  "ident": {
    "text": "CCI-004922",
    "system": "http://cyber.mil/cci"
  },
  "id": "xccdf_mil.disa.stig_rule_SV-263661r982567_rule",
  "selected": "true",
  "role": "full",
  "severity": "medium"
}

