{
  "title": {
    "text": "The operating system must protect the confidentiality\n                        and integrity of transmitted information.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "description": {
    "text": "Without protection of the transmitted\n                        information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because\n                        unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered.\n                        This requirement applies to both internal and external networks and all\n                        types of information system components from which information can be\n                        transmitted (e.g., servers, mobile devices, notebook computers, printers,\n                        copiers, scanners, and facsimile machines). Communication paths outside the\n                        physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility\n                        of interception and modification.\n\n                        Protecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information\n                        can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution\n                        systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If\n                        physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography)\n                        do not have to be employed, and vice versa.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "rationale": {
    "text": "Linux containers do not automatically make open ports available\n                        to the host or network where the container is being run. If ports are\n                        opened, they must first be configured during the startup of the container\n                        image to expose the application to the network. A host configured to meet\n                        STIG requirements will only enable those ports necessary for the operation\n                        of the running container to operate. Once exposed by the host configuration,\n                        the open ports will be filtered and monitored using the host’s firewall and\n                        associated auditing and security capabilities.\n\n                        For more information on inherited controls for containers see the DISA\n                        Container Hardening Process Guide.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "platform": {
    "idref": "cpe:/o:notapplicable"
  },
  "ident": {
    "text": "CCI-002418",
    "system": "http://cyber.mil/cci"
  },
  "id": "xccdf_mil.disa.stig_rule_SV-203748r958908_rule",
  "selected": "true",
  "role": "full",
  "severity": "high"
}

