{
  "title": {
    "text": "The operating system must enable an application\n                        firewall, if available.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "description": {
    "text": "Firewalls protect computers from network attacks\n                        by blocking or limiting access to open network ports. Application firewalls\n                        limit which applications are allowed to communicate over the network.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "rationale": {
    "text": "Linux containers inherit the firewall configuration of their host\n                        operating system which dictates which ports on the container can be accessed\n                        from the network. Selection of which ports to make accessible on the\n                        applications running on the container is the responsibility of the host\n                        firewall configuration - an additional application-level firewall inside the\n                        container is not necessary.\n\n                        For more information on inherited controls for containers see the DISA\n                        Container Hardening Process Guide.",
