{
  "title": {
    "text": "The operating system must implement address space\n                        layout randomization to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "description": {
    "text": "Some adversaries launch attacks with the intent\n                        of executing code in non-executable regions of memory or in memory locations\n                        that are prohibited. Security safeguards employed to protect memory include,\n                        for example, data execution prevention and address space layout\n                        randomization. Data execution prevention safeguards can either be\n                        hardware-enforced or software-enforced with hardware providing the greater\n                        strength of mechanism.\n\n                        Examples of attacks are buffer overflow attacks.\n                    ",
    "lang": "en"
  },
  "ident": {
